The path to your future starts at eastern!

Eastern is a public university with a private college atmosphere. Live and study on a beautiful campus, get to know your professors and make lifelong friends. Gain hands-on experience in your major as you prepare for a successful career. Fit in and stand out!

Undergraduates can choose from 41 majors, 65 minors and more than 60 concentrations. Everything from Accounting to World Languages and Cultures. Graduate programs and continuing education opportunities are also available.
90 percent of freshmen and 60 percent of all students live on campus. Live close to classes, the  library, computing resources, and student activities â get better grades and graduate on time!
More than 90 student clubs and organizations, including co-curricular, cultural, club sports,  art/music, and more. Canât find one you like? Start your own! People to meet and things to do!

Eastern has 18 varsity sports ranging from baseball to volleyball and competes in NCAA Division III. The Warriors have won nine national titles and own the best athletic record in the Little East Conference.

Eastern supports healthy minds and bodies with a range of fitness, wellness and recreational activities. Work out in the fitness center, participate in intramurals, practice yoga or join a club sports team.

2,500 events a year include concerts, lectures, plays, etc. Gain cultural perspectives from a student-run radio station, a new arts center and programs that support women, the LGBT community and a diverse community.
Going to college is fun yet challenging âbut we will have your back! Services range from career  counseling to health services and financial aid, from campus ministries to the Veterans Center.
Eastern undergraduates conduct faculty-mentored research in every majorâeverything from genetics  to theater set design.
Dozens of internships provide you with hands-on experiences related to your major â a stepping stone  to future employment.
Gain professional experience and leadership skills volunteering for local social agencies and nonprofits,  or take a service-learning course connected to your major.
Take a âglobal field courseâ or study for a semester in one of more than 130 countries. Or study at  another U.S. university!

I will never forget my experiences in Belize and San Salvador Island; those opportunities helped define my career aspirations and provided a great deal of practical experience.â

Eastern students graduate with strong problem-solving, communication and teambuilding skills in dozens of career fields. They become doctors, attorneys, accountants, teachers and social workers in Connecticut and throughout the nation and the world. Eastern alumni include world- class scientists, nationally recognized artists and award-winning authors. You could be one!
